    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                One of the angles of a regular polygon is 40¬∞ and its sides are 15 cm long. Sketch the polygon and
                then find the area of the polygon.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                üîπ From the defination of a polygon all interior angle add up to <m>360^ \circ</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
               üîπ To find the number of sides of a triangle we use the formula <m>\frac{360}{\text{Interior angle}} = \text{Number of sides}</m>. Where <m>n</m> is the number opf sides.
            </p>
            <p> <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{360^ \circ}{\text{interior angle}} = \amp \text{Number of sides} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac{360^\circ}{40} = \amp 9 \text{sides}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                üîπFinding the area of the nenagon we use the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                Area of a tringle using sine rule <m>\times the number of sides </m> Where our ab is the radii..
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \frac{1}{2}absin 40^\circ \theta = \amp \frac {1}{2} \times 15\text{cm} \times 15\text{cm} \times  sin 40^\circ \theta </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 225 \times 0.6428 \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md> 
            </p>
            <p>
               üîπ There are 9 triangles since a nenagon has 9 sides.
            </p>
            <p>
                üîπTherefore, total area is:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>  = \amp 9 \times  (\frac{1}{2} \times 225 \times 0.6428 ) </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 9 \times 225 \times 0.3214 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 73.6006 \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
